The ode begins as a song of exultation on hearing the news of Cleo· patra’s death, which reached Rome in September, 30 ne. But in v. 21, after applying the opprobrious fatale nmnstrum to the queen, Horace suddenly changes to a feeling of admiration for the heroic courage with which she faced death and cheated the Romans of half the glory of their triumph. With this ode should be compared Epod. 9, written in celebra· tion of the victory at Actium. It is noteworthy that in neither is An- tony mentioned, the poet forbearing to glory over a fellow Roman. The poem is probably rnodeled on Alcaeus’ ode on the death of the tyrant Myrsilus, in any case the enthusiastic verses with which Horace opens were suggested by the verses of Alcaeus preserved by Athen. 10, 430 A.
